{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_016efkijPBgtftVCFuJuD6r4","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture of what's configured. Let me summarize what's non-default:\n\n**Index settings on `audit-index`:**\n- `index.number_of_shards: 3` (default is 1)\n- `index.number_of_replicas: 1` (this is actually the default, so no change needed)\n- `index.routing.allocation.require.tier: hot` (non-default - this requires shards to be allocated only to nodes with `tier=hot` attribute)\n- `index.routing.allocation.include._tier_preference: data_content` (this is the default in ES 8.x for ILM-managed indices, but it's explicit here)\n- `number_of_shards: 3` (confirmed as non-default)\n\nThe cluster has no persistent or transient settings applied via the API, and all nodes are configured with the `tier: hot` attribute at the node level rather than through Elasticsearch settings. The cluster settings API shows no persistent or transient settings have been applied through the API, but the node attributes with `tier: hot` are configured directly in the elasticsearch.yml file, which enables the shard allocation routing requirement. So the non-default configuration includes the `audit-index` with custom shard count and tier-based routing, plus the node-level tier attributes that support that routing.\n\nFor the rollback script, I need to remove the routing allocation constraints by setting them to null, though the shard count itself is immutable and can't be changed without deleting and recreating the index. The replica count is already at default, so that doesn't need adjustment. Writing the rollback script... Writing shell commands... Writing the rollback script...","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4186,"cache_read_input_tokens":29778,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1